Nord Stream, new port of Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream Remote Gas pipeline connecting directly eastern Europe to Russia and led by the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to work.
They must supply gas equal to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, among them 4 bosses of states and governments, took part in the Nord Stream inauguration last Tuesday, a new pipeline that connects directly to Russia and Germany under the sea.
Symbolically German Chancellor Angela Merkelová, Russian President Dmitrij Medveděv, French Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned together by controlling the control valve of the Russian gas input into the Western European network.
This new gas pipeline begins to flow every year to the western Europe 27,5 billion additional cubic gas meters by the first tube of 1,224 km connecting the Petrohrad region with the mecklemburg-Pomorian Federal Land.
The second pipes to be completed at the end of 2012 will allow a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, which is a quantity equal to the entire French consumption.
And it is already recalled the possibility to build the third pipeline of gas pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this enormous building has the nature of the victory.
Against the project, Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany without being driven by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing somewhat power: the possibility of pushing Russia with threats that will close him access to the Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
The most powerfully expressed this to Warsaw when she did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "the new German-Soviet Pact" with appeal to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin at the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means that it's politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained greater confidence in its purchases by supporting this Russian project.
