"Gazprom will have a profit from the total capacity, whether the amount of real-transported gas is any," says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of gas pipeline was secured from 30% of shareholders and 70% of bank loans.
The total cost of work should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipes.
For the GDF Suez Group, investment costs amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will return, because the risk is taken only by Gazprom.
Gas pipeline is coming from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy coast with pine forests.
A high 4,5 meter vents form an output gas gate.
The sensors measure pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the coming gas before being transported into the German gas pipelines.
From last Tuesday, this terminal has received one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
